<div class="nine_section_1" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<h3 class="first_paragraph">NO COUNTRY FOR OLD MEN</h3>
			<p>
				What is this film about? Let's try applying some of the terminology we've been discussing this semester to see whether we can shed any light on this question. 
			</p>
			<p>
				We’ll start by asking the following questions: Who are the main characters? Are the characters complex or simple? What are their traits? Do they drive the cause-and-effect chain? How cohesive is the cause/effect chain? Are there conspicuous deviations from traditional narrative practice?
			</p>
			<p>
				The first character we meet is Anton in a rather graphically unpleasant introduction. It seems pretty clear that he's the antagonist in this film rather than the protagonist. Modern films don’t necessarily split the characters into easily identifiable categories of “good” and “bad”, but based on what happens in this film, it’s relatively easy to classify him as an antagonist, largely because he poses the primary opposition to the goals of the other main characters in the film. Chigurh may qualify as “evil,” but he’s hardly a simple character. He’s characterized as a humorless psychopath, but he’s also a “principled” man who’s bound by his own skewed sense of honor and committed to following a rigid set of rules rather than simply pursuing his own self-interest. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Next, we're introduced to Llewelyn Moss. We get information about his traits: he’s tough, resourceful, independent, stubborn, but has a “good heart” as evidenced by his decision to revisit the scene of the crime with a jug of water. We follow his goal to keep the money and elude those chasing him for most of the rest of the film. Based on these things, it would seem like he qualifies as the protagonist of the film. He’s also a highly complex character. He’s motivated by the baser desires of greed, self-interest and vengeance (things we’d typically expect from the villain). He also exhibits more admirable qualities of resourcefulness, toughness, and a relatively soft heart. He has no interest in doing anyone else wrong for no reason. However, he’s also stubborn, and his stubbornness ends up getting his wife, one of the only blameless people in the film, killed.
			</p>
			<p>
				Another important character in the film is sheriff Bell, played by Tommy Lee Jones. We're not introduced to him until almost a half-hour in (when he's talking about there being a "car afar"––I LOVE the Southern dialect and details in this film, like the woman who "ain't allowed to give out no im-for-mation"). Sheriff Bell seems like a relatively minor character, somewhat hard to categorize in our traditional model. We learn very little about him for the majority of the film. He joins the story fairly late. He poses no threat to the protagonist, and in fact, never even interacts with him. He’s only chasing him to try to help him. However, there are some unusual things that happen in this film that change his role in the film as we go on. 
			</p>
			<p>
				First, the protagonist is abruptly and unceremoniously killed off with about a half hour left in the film. It’s a highly unusual strategy.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
