<div class="nine_section_2" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				The killing of Moss is an unexpected gut-punch for the viewer. We’ve been led to believe that Moss is the hero, and we expect the hero to win out in the end. His death basically provides the end of the cause-and-effect chain that was begun by Moss’s traits and goals, and it should essentially mark the end of the film. Moss failed to retain the money or elude his enemies (though his end isn’t brought about by his strongest opposition, Chigurh). Those are the things we were watching the movie to find out. However, the movie continues on for another 25 - 30 minutes, centering almost entirely around the sheriff, with one final scene with Chigurh. 				
			</p>
			<p>
				If the film were “about” Moss, either as a character study, or as a plot-based film centered around his quest to achieve his goals, it more or less has to end when that quest is over. However, the fact that it continues on long after he’s gone suggests that his role in the film is actually only supplementary, there to support some other, larger goal. It’s the character of the sheriff that comes to the fore in the last part of the movie, as we see him wrestling with the things he’s seen, as well as dealing with his own age and sense of mortality. I find the sheriff’s role to be highly unusual. Ultimately, he figures largely as a proxy for the viewer, there to provide us with a guide as to how we should be feeling as we observe the events of the film, as though the filmmakers have actually inserted the observing audience into the story itself. He trails along after the action of the plot, often revisiting the set of the previous scene that we’ve just watched in order to provide some sort of commentary or emotional cue. It’s through his eyes that we first see Moss’s dead body on the ground, as the filmmakers skip over the actual shooting and just show the sheriff riding up to the aftermath. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Ultimately, when trying to decipher what this film is “about”, I think we have to conclude that like <em>2001: A Space Odyssey</em> this film is more about ideas than about characters or plot (though it’s clearly far more invested in both character and plot than was <em>2001</em>). Though there’s a fairly tightly woven cause-and-effect chain for the first three-quarters of the film, the plot comes to an abrupt end, and the film continues on. Though the film provides portraits of complex characters, the character we identify with most is removed from the film long before it ends. Ultimately this film is about wrestling with and against the idea of the “happy ending”. It gives us an unhappy ending, and then gives us another half-hour to come to grips with it. It sets up the notion of the resourceful everyman who somehow overcomes all odds to achieve his goals and work his will on the world, only to make a point of saying that that fantasy is not the way the world actually works. That, then, is the theme of this film: that the world does not work the way that we want it to. The actions of the film feel heartless and brutal, and we’re tempted, like sheriff Bell, to feel like what we’re seeing is evidence of the spiraling decay of humanity’s descent into greater brutality. But the film chides us for thinking that, essentially saying “what you’ve got is nothing new”. The world has always been a place filled with brutality and random chance. And as sheriff Bell relates his dream at the end of the film, we’re left with some small glimmer of hope in the knowledge that, despite all of the brutality, we’re not alone. Others have gone before us and dealt with the same things. It’s only a glimmer of hope. But maybe, in the face of hopelessness, that’s not such a small thing.
			</p>
			<h3>STYLE IN NO COUNTRY FOR OLD MEN</h3>
			<p>
				I’d like to spend some time looking at one aspect of the stylistic approach chosen by the Coen brothers: sound design. The soundtrack of the film is naturalistic and strictly diegetic––to an unusual degree.  There’s no soundtrack music whatsoever in this film. 	
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
