<div class="nine_section_3" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				In order to talk about the impact of the sound, I’ll back up for a minute and talk about another facet of the film: its sense of atmosphere. When we talk about a film’s atmosphere, we’re talking about how much the film succeeds in making you feel that you’re a part of the space in which the film is happening. We watch films in a space completely abstracted from the space in which the story is supposed to be happening, yet through two of our five senses, cinema can make an attempt to immerse us in the world of the story. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Sound is actually one of the more pivotal components in determining how immersive a film is for the viewer. When non-diegetic music is laid over the imagery that we’re watching it may provide certain emotional cues for the viewer (that’s typically why music is used), but it also provides a layer of removal from the immediacy of the moment being depicted. Whether or not the viewer is thinking about it consciously, she’s aware that in the real world music does not accompany our daily activities, so hearing a musical score over something emphasizes that we’re not actually a part of what’s happening on screen.
			</p>
			<p>
				 The filmmaker is making a trade-off between emotional specificity and atmosphere. The Coen brothers’ commitment to using only diegetic sound means that the viewers are given less of a cue as to how they are supposed to feel during a scene, but it also draws the viewer more deeply into the moments that are occurring onscreen. 
			</p>
			<p>
				More specifically, one of the ways the Coen brothers generate a vivid sense of atmosphere in this film is through the evocation of multiple sense perceptions. Think back to the scene with Moss at the shootout. He finds one of the people injured but alive in the truck. That character is asking for water. His lips are chapped and dried out. We hear flies buzzing. We hear the wind blowing. We can nearly feel his thirst. As Moss sets out after the “ultimo hombre” or the last man standing, he talks about the intense heat. 
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
