			<h3 class="first_paragraph">THE PUZZLE FILM</h3>
			<p>
				In our continuing look at different patterns of storytelling, this week we’ll look at the genre of the puzzle film. It’s a genre that has evolved out of the mystery/detective genre. 
			</p>
			<p>
				In the puzzle film, just like in the mystery film, narration is highly restricted, as the filmmaker raises questions in the viewer by withholding strategic information. The viewer gradually uncovers information incrementally along with the characters. 
			</p>
			<p>
				The puzzle film differs from the detective story in that the director is willing to create a sense of confusion and disorientation rather than simply raising the viewer’s curiosity. Another difference of the puzzle film is that the questions raised by the film may not be simply about the events and characters but about the world of the film itself, as viewers are often forced to reevaluate what they thought they understood about the film after certain revelations occur.
			</p>
			<p>
				Some examples from the genre include <em>Fight Club, Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind, Adaptation, Inception, Memento, The Prestige</em> (most Christopher Nolan films really), <em>The Usual Suspects, Primer, The Sixth Sense</em>. It’s a fairly popular genre these days.
			</p>
			<p>
				One of the hallmarks of the puzzle film is exceptionally tight control exerted over the discourse. Which events are included from the story, the order in which those events are presented, even which details are actually seen from the events that are displayed, are all carefully chosen by the director. In the puzzle film, nearly any other presentation of the materials of the story would give away some crucial element of the puzzle before the intended revelation. 
			</p>
			<p>
				This extremely controlled presentation of the materials of the story brings up an issue that we’ll talk more about later in the semester, but is worth raising here: the question of the degree of manipulation in cinema.
			</p>
			<p>
				Any film is a manipulative experience. We’re being shown certain events to the exclusion of others. We are shown those events from a certain visual perspective exclusive of all others. The viewer can be easily misled through this selective disbursement of information. The puzzle film, however, is more manipulative than the typical film. One of its primary goals is the intentional misleading of the audience. Is there such a thing as too much manipulation or contexts in which manipulation is a bad thing? From one perspective, manipulation is unavoidable, but from another perspective, manipulation is essentially lying to the viewer. Then again, it’s doing so to provide the viewer with an experience that they’re often looking for. Is there such a thing as too much manipulation? We’ll tackle that question more in-depth at some point later in the semester, but I want you to be thinking about the role manipulation plays in the films you watch as we continue throughout the semester.
			</p>
			<h3>MULHOLLAND DRIVE</h3>
			<p>
				Even among puzzle films, <em>Mulholland Drive</em> is rather unusually obscure, raising far more questions than it answers. As you watch <em>Mulholland Drive</em> by David Lynch, here are some questions to think about (though you’ll probably have plenty of your own questions to chew on relating to the film itself). How is Lynch’s use of technique similar to traditional Hollywood filmmaking, and where do his methods break from traditional practice? How does Lynch use viewer expectation and psychology to create his puzzle? 
			</p>
